<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-279-746  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 279 746.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  March 19 1990 v9 n6 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army considers moratorium on ADP systems development.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyNational GovernmentMilitaryEDP BudgetingPlanningEquipment AcquisitionSystem DevelopmentUnited States. Army.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Army Considers Moratorium On ADP Systems DevelopmentandM;The Army has begun receiving comments on whether it should halt systemsdevelopment, as proposed by its chief information resources managementofficial.andM;Lt.andP;  Gen.andP;  Jerome B. Hilmes, the Army's director of information systems forcommand, control, communications and computers (DISC4), had asked field-levelinformation managers how a moratorium would affect their operations.andM;Maj.andP;  Nancy Burt, an Army spokeswoman, said she was not sure if the commentswould be compiled when Hilmes testified on the Army's IRM operations nextmonth before the House Appropriations Subcommittee on Defense.andP;  She said itwas too soon to speculate on the substance of the responses.andM;Burt said the proposed moratorium would exclude &quot;various war-fighting andadministrative systems.&quot;andM;Hilmes proposed the moratorium partly in response to the Defense Departmenteffort to integrate the military services' systems under the new DODcorporate information management (CIM) plan, Burt said.andP;  The CIM wouldstandardize requirements for systems in seven functional areas.andM;Although Burt described Hilmes' congressional appearance as &quot;a normallyscheduled thing,&quot; sources said Hilmes specifically asked to testify.andM;Last year subcommittee members questioned the former DISC4, now-retired Lt.andO;Gen.andP;  Bruce R. Harris, about ADP issues.andM;A Capitol Hill source said government officials rarely ask to testify beforea congressional committee, but Hilmes' request was not unusual because thesubcommittee had targeted the Army last year.andM;&quot;Now that he's in charge and doing some things differently, he wants to comeup and explain them,&quot; the source said.andP;  &quot;It's only fair that there be afollow-up.&quot;andM;Army officials declined to comment on what Hilmes will discuss at thehearing.andO;</TEXT></DOC>